{{Refimprove|date=November 2008}}

There is no cross-border [[flag]] universally accepted as representing both jurisdictions on the island of [[Ireland]]. This can be a problem in contexts where a body organised on an all-island basis needs to be represented by a flag in an international context. 

The island is politically divided into the [[Republic of Ireland]] (a sovereign state comprising 26 of Ireland's 32 traditional counties) and [[Northern Ireland]] (comprising the remaining 6 counties in the north-east of Ireland, and a part of the [[United Kingdom]]), but all-island organisations are common. Examples include the [[Roman Catholicism in Ireland|Roman Catholic Church in Ireland]], the Presbyterian Church in Ireland and the [[Church of Ireland]], the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]], and the [[Irish Rugby Football Union]].

==Saint Patrick's Saltire==
{{Main|Saint Patrick's Saltire}}
{{Weasel|section|date=February 2013}}
[[File:St Patrick's saltire.svg|thumb|right|upright|Saint Patrick's Saltire]]
The Saint Patrick's [[Saltire]] was incorporated into the [[Union Flag]] in 1801 by way of the [[Act of Union 1800]] to represent Ireland within the new [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. Today, those who regard the [[tricolour (flag)|tricolour]] as specific to the Republic of Ireland, or excluding unionists, may advocate it as a neutral symbol of the whole island.

The [[Church of Ireland]] orders that, apart from the [[flag of the Anglican Communion]], only this saltire may be flown on its church grounds—as opposed to the tricolour, the Union Flag or the [[Ulster banner|former flag of Northern Ireland]]. This follows the practice of other Anglican churches in England, Scotland, and Wales, which fly the flags of their respective patron saints instead of the Union Flag.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ireland.anglican.org/index.php?do=information&id=49|title= Church Of Ireland General Synod Sub Committee On Sectarianism Report|date=April 1999|author=Church of Ireland|authorlink=Church of Ireland}}: ''Resolution One: The General Synod of the Church of Ireland recognises that from time to time confusion and controversy have attended the flying of flags on church buildings or within the grounds of church buildings. This Synod therefore resolves that the only flags specifically authorised to be flown on church buildings or within the church grounds of the Church of Ireland are the cross of St Patrick or, alternatively, the [[Flag of the Anglican Communion|flag of the Anglican Communion bearing the emblem of the Compassrose]]. Such flags are authorised to be flown only on Holy Days and during the Octaves of Christmas, Easter, the Ascension of Our Lord and Pentecost, and on any other such day as may be recognised locally as the Dedication Day of the particular church building. Any other flag flown at any other time is not specifically authorised by this Church.''</ref>

The saltire is also flown by [[St. Patrick's College, Maynooth]], on graduation days, and so it can be argued that St. Patrick's Saltire is used by the main Protestant church on the island and the Roman Catholic Church.

Modified versions have been used formerly by the [[Irish Rugby Football Union]], and currently by the [[Royal College of Surgeons in Ireland]] and the [[Commissioners of Irish Lights]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dillon |first=Jim |year=1995 |title=The Evolution of Maritime Uniform |journal=Beam |publisher=Commissioners of Irish Lights |volume=24 |quote=In the Lighthouse Service the cap badge originally was a St George's Cross surrounded by a wreath of laurel leaves but from 1970 the St Patrick's Cross has been used. |url=http://www.commissionersofirishlights.com/cil/publications/beam-magazines/volume-24/the-evolution-of-maritime-uniform.aspx |accessdate=27 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013111549/http://www.commissionersofirishlights.com/cil/publications/beam-magazines/volume-24/the-evolution-of-maritime-uniform.aspx |archivedate=13 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Irish tricolour==
{{main|Flag of Ireland}}
[[File:Flag of Ireland.svg|thumb|upright|Flag of the State of Ireland]]
The tricolour of green, white and orange, the official flag of the state of Ireland, is considered by [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalists]], to represent the entire island as well. [[Gerry Adams]] said in [[Dáil Éireann]] in 2011:<ref>[http://debates.oireachtas.ie/dail/2011/03/09/00008.asp#N167 Dáil debates Vol.728 No.1 p.8 c.52]</ref>
{{quote|Above this Chamber flies the flag of this nation — all Thirty-Two Counties — the flag of green, white and orange.}}

However, this symbolism is rejected by [[Ulster unionism|Ulster unionist]]s, as illustrated by an exchange in the [[House of Commons of Northern Ireland]] in 1951:<ref>{{cite hansard |url=http://stormontpapers.ahds.ac.uk/stormontpapers/pageview.html?volumeno=35&pageno=2093&searchTerm=tricolour#bak-35-2073 |date=21 August 1951 |volume=35 |house=Commons N.I. |column=2073}}</ref> 
*[[James McSparran]] (''[[Nationalist Party (Northern Ireland)|Nationalist Party]]''): The tricolour is admitted by all nations within the comity of nations to be the national flag of Ireland.
*Honorable members: No.
*McSparran: We are having interruptions already. It is the national flag of the Irish Republic.
*[[William May (politician)|William May]] (''[[Ulster Unionist Party]]''): That is better.

The [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) flies this flag at matches regardless of whether either or both teams are from Northern Ireland. It is also used for the [[Ireland international rules football team]], selected by the GAA on an all-island basis.

The [[Golfing Union of Ireland]] covers the whole island and competes under the tricolour in international events such as the [[World Cup (men's golf)|World Cup]], [[Alfred Dunhill Cup]] and the [[Eisenhower Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/golf/mcdowell-and-mcginley-fly-the-flag-for-ireland-1520061.html|title=McDowell and McGinley fly the flag for Ireland|last=MacGinty |first=Karl|date=November 4, 2008|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2008-11-07}}</ref>

==Four Provinces flag==
{{multiple image |total_width=330 |image1=Four Provinces Flag.svg |width1=1320 |height1=680 |caption1=The Four Provinces flag is composed of the flags of (clockwise from top left) [[Flag of Munster|Munster]], [[Flag and coat of arms of Connacht|Connacht]], [[Flag and coat of arms of Leinster|Leinster]], and [[Flag of Ulster|Ulster]]. |image2=ShannonErne.svg |width2=900 |height2=600 |caption2=The Erne flag}}
{{main|Four Provinces Flag of Ireland}}
The four provinces flag is a [[quartering (heraldry)|quartering]] of the arms of the four [[provinces of Ireland]]. The order of the provinces varies.

==Erne flag==
This flag was initially used on the [[Shannon–Erne Waterway]], which is bisected by the border. Rather than flying a national flag, boats fly this green, white and blue flag.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lough Erne Flag & IWAI Pennants|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119141529/http://erne.iwai.ie/flagpennant.html |archivedate=19 November 2007 |url=http://erne.iwai.ie/flagpennant.html|work=Lough Erne Flag|publisher=IWAI|accessdate=12 August 2010}}{{failed verification|date=September 2011}}</ref> It is endorsed by the [[Inland Waterways Association of Ireland]], an all-island organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shop.iwai.ie/catalog/product_info.php?cPath=23&products_id=101|title=Erne Flag|publisher=Inland Waterways Association of Ireland|accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref>

==Harp flags==
{{Further|Coat of arms of Ireland}}
{{multiple image |total_width=330 |image1=Flag of the President of Ireland.svg |caption1=[[Presidential Standard (Ireland)|Presidential Standard]] of the [[President of Ireland]] |image2=Royal Standard of Ireland (1542–1801).svg |caption2=Quarter of the Royal Standard }}
The [[harp]] (or ''{{lang|ga|[[clàrsach|cláirseach]]}}'') has long been a symbol of Ireland.  It first featured on [[Irish coins]] in the reign of [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] around 1534.<ref name="morris12">
{{cite book |last=Morris |first=Ewan |title=Our own devices: National symbols and polititcal conflict in Twentieth-Century Ireland |publisher=Irish Academic Press |year=2005 |pages=12 |isbn=0-7165-2663-8}}
</ref> During the seventeenth and eighteenth century, the harp became adorned with progressively more decoration, ultimately becoming a "winged maiden".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fotw.us/Flags/ie-green.html|title=Ireland: Green Flag |last=Burgers |first=Andries |date=21 May 2006 |publisher=[[Flags of the World]] |accessdate=1 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051230034339/http://www.fotw.us/flags/ie-green.html |archivedate=30 December 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Boydell |first=Barra |title=Irish Musical Studies |editor=Patrick F. Devine & Harry White |publisher=Four Courts Press |year=1996 |volume=5 |chapter=The Iconography of the Irish Harp as a National Symbol |isbn=1-85182-261-5 }}</ref>  In the nineteenth century, the ''Maid of Erin'', a [[national personification|personification]] of Ireland, was a woman holding a more realistic harp than the "winged maiden". This style of harp was then also used in Irish flags.  The harp on the modern coat of arms of Ireland is modelled on the "[[Brian Boru]]" harp in the library of [[Trinity College, Dublin]], as it appeared after an 1840s restoration.

===Blue harp flag===
The lower left quadrant of the [[Royal Standard of the United Kingdom]] has featured a harp on a blue field, representing Ireland since 1603.<ref name="morris12"/>  The current version, designed in 1953, uses a winged-maiden harp and consists of a golden ''{{lang|ga|[[clàrsach|cláirseach]]}}'' with silver strings on a blue background. The shade of blue in the field was known as [[Saint Patrick's Blue]] when used in 1783 for the regalia of the [[Order of Saint Patrick]].<ref>
{{cite journal |last=Cullen |first=Fintan |year=1995 |title=Visual Politics in 1780s Ireland: The Roles of History Painting |journal=Oxford Art Journal |volume= 18 |issue= 1 |pages=65 |jstor=1360595 |publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref>

===Green harp flag===
{{multiple image |total_width=330 |image1=Naval_jack_of_Ireland.svg |caption1=Naval Jack of Ireland |image2=Green harp flag of Ireland.svg |caption2=Flag of the United Irishmen }}
The change from blue to green is associated with the [[United Irishmen]], an [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalist]] movement associated with both Catholic and Protestant Irish — its leader [[Wolfe Tone]] was Protestant; green was a colour of [[rebellion]] in the eighteenth century.<ref>[http://www.military.ie/naval/uniform/flags/ Naval Service - Flags and Pennants] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323015606/http://www.military.ie/naval/uniform/flags/ |date=23 March 2009 }}</ref> This was a common flag used to represent Ireland during the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. It consisted of a gold ''{{lang|ga|cláirseach}}'' on a green background. It was associated with moderate nationalism at a time when the tricolour was confined to more radical movements. It is the same as the modern [[Flag of Leinster]].
{{clear}}

==Sporting flags==
{{multiple image |total_width=330 |image1=Cricket Ireland flag.svg |caption1=Ireland cricket team flag |image2=Flag of Ireland hockey team.svg |caption2=Ireland hockey team flag |image3= Flag of Quidditch Ireland.svg |caption3= Flag of [[Quidditch (sport)|Quidditch]] Ireland}}
Several all-island sporting organisations send representative teams to compete internationally.  In some cases, a flag unique to that organisation is used in lieu of a national flag.  Typically such flags include one of the traditional [[:Category:National symbols of Ireland|symbols of Ireland]].

The [[Ireland cricket team]] uses a blue flag depicting [[shamrock]]s.

The [[Ireland men's national field hockey team|Ireland national field hockey team]] uses a bespoke flag with a shield quartered with the symbols of the four provinces.

[[File:IRFU flag.svg|thumb|left|upright|Ireland rugby team flag]]
The [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland rugby team]]'s flag is a green flag containing the shields of the four provinces and the [[Irish Rugby Football Union]]'s logo.  At matches outside Ireland, this is the only flag displayed. At matches in Northern Ireland (typically at [[Ravenhill Stadium|Ravenhill]]) the [[Flag of Ulster]] (yellow background) is also displayed.  This is the flag of the nine-county province (including the three Ulster counties in the Republic of Ireland), similar to but distinct from the [[Ulster Banner]] (white background), the former flag of the [[Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] government.  At matches in the Republic of Ireland (typically at [[Lansdowne Road]]), the Irish tricolour is flown along with the preceding two.

[[Eddie Irvine]], a [[Formula One]] driver from [[Conlig]] in Northern Ireland, asked for a white flag with a shamrock to be used if he secured a [[Podium#Usage in motorsport|podium finish]].<ref name="it-irvine">{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/features/2009/0623/1224249332136.html  |title=Sporting political gestures |date=23 June 2009|work=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=2009-06-23}}
</ref> There had been controversy when an Irish tricolour had been used incorrectly for him [[1997 Argentine Grand Prix|in 1997]].<ref name="it-irvine"/> The [[Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] insisted the Union Flag be used in conformance with its regulations.<ref name="it-irvine"/>
{{clear}}

The Show Jumping Association of Ireland (SJAI; subsequently renamed [[Showjumping Ireland]]) used a green flag with its crest based on the four provinces when competing internationally, from its formation after the Second World War. In [[FEI Nations Cup]] events, Ireland was represented by the [[Irish Army Equitation School]] under the tricolour. From the late 1960s,  the SJAI joined forces with the army in  [[International Federation for Equestrian Sports|FEI]] competitions and competed under the tricolour, although it retained its own flag in other competitions until the late 1970s.<ref name="Slavin1998">{{cite book|last=Slavin|first=Michael|title=Showjumping Legends: Ireland, 1868-1998|year=1998|publisher=Wolfhound Press|isbn=9780863276576|page=55}}</ref>

